<BaseLayout title={title} description={description}>
  <h1>What to Do If You're Paid Late</h1>
  <p>Whether you're a vendor with an overdue invoice or an employee whose paycheck is late, the recovery process follows similar steps.</p>

  <h2>For B2B / overdue invoices</h2>

  <h3>Step 1: Send a clear reminder</h3>
  <p>Many late payments are oversight rather than refusal. A polite email referencing the invoice number, original due date, and current balance often resolves the issue within a few days.</p>

  <h3>Step 2: Send a formal demand letter</h3>
  <p>If informal reminders fail, send a formal demand letter. Include:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>Original invoice and payment terms</li>
    <li>Current balance plus any contractual late fees and interest</li>
    <li>A reasonable deadline (typically 10&ndash;14 days)</li>
    <li>What happens if payment isn't received (collections, legal action)</li>
  </ul>
  <p>Keep it factual and professional. Send by certified mail with return receipt for evidence.</p>

  <h3>Step 3: Consider mediation or arbitration</h3>
  <p>If your contract specifies arbitration, that's likely your forum. Some states have free or low-cost commercial mediation programs.</p>

  <h3>Step 4: File suit (small claims for small amounts)</h3>
  <p>Small claims court handles debts up to $5,000&ndash;$10,000 depending on state. You can usually file without an attorney. Above small-claims limits, weigh whether an attorney makes economic sense.</p>

  <h3>Step 5: Collections agency (last resort)</h3>
  <p>Selling the debt or hiring a collections agency typically recovers 30&ndash;70% of face value, but ends your direct involvement.</p>

  <h2>For employment / late final paycheck</h2>

  <h3>Step 1: Send a written demand</h3>
  <p>Email HR or payroll with your final paycheck calculation. State the legal deadline if you know it (e.g., "California Labor Code &sect; 203 required payment immediately at termination"). Be specific and professional.</p>

  <h3>Step 2: File with your state labor agency (free)</h3>
  <p>Most states have a free wage-claim process. California has the Labor Commissioner's Office. Other states have similar agencies. Filing is free and doesn't require an attorney.</p>

  <h3>Step 3: Consider an employment attorney</h3>
  <p>For larger amounts or potential statutory penalties, attorneys can often recover more than agency claims, especially with attorney's fees provisions in most state wage laws. Many work on contingency.</p>

  <h3>Step 4: Federal claim if applicable</h3>
  <p>You can also file with the US Department of Labor's Wage and Hour Division for federal FLSA claims. Federal and state remedies are generally separate.</p>

  <h2>What NOT to do (either context)</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Don't make threats you can't back up.</strong> "I'll sue tomorrow" sounds weak when you don't.</li>
    <li><strong>Don't disparage the debtor publicly.</strong> Creates defamation exposure.</li>
    <li><strong>Don't accept partial payment as full settlement</strong> without a written release saying so.</li>
    <li><strong>Don't wait past the statute of limitations.</strong> Varies by state and claim type; for written contracts typically 4&ndash;6 years.</li>
  </ul>
</BaseLayout>
